# Goal

- [https://stackstate.atlassian.net/browse/STAC-22567](https://stackstate.atlassian.net/browse/STAC-22567)

# Problem

1. OpenTelemetry data are processed in two places: otel collector and Sync component.Otel Collector converts Spans  to Components and Relations. The implementation is hardcoded. Then these Components and Relations are processed by almost “generic” synchronization.   
2. It works for current OpenTelemetry services but it isn’t generic enough to work with any OpenTelemetry like GenAI.  
3. Two step implementation doesn't allow to create StackPack for generic Components represented by OpenTelemetry spans.

## Components specification

#### OtelComponent \- creates a topology component form Otel Span

| Field path | Type | Mandatory | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| \_type | String, expected value **OtelCompoenentMapping** | yes |  |
| output.identifier | String Expression with placeholders | yes | Unique identifier of the component. All placeholders are mandatory. The component won’t be created If at least one placeholder is missing  |
| output.name | String Expression with placeholders | yes |  |
| output.layer | String Expression with placeholders | yes |  |
| output.domain | String Expression with placeholders | yes |  |
| output.type.name | String Expression with placeholders | yes | Type of the component to create, even if the expression accepts placeholders the cardinality should be low.  |
| output.required | Map\[String, String Expression\] or Map\[String, Array\[StringExpression\]\] | optional | Dictionary with list of required attributes of the component. Key \- name of the property, Value \- String Expression with placeholders. All placeholders are mandatory. If at least one of the placeholder is missing then the synchronisation workflow will throw an error and the component won’t be created. |
| output.required.tags | Map\[String, String Expression\] OR MergeOperator | optional | Dictionary with list of required tags/labels of the component. Key \- name of the tag, Value \- String Expression with placeholders. All placeholders are mandatory. If at least one of the placeholder is missing then the synchronisation workflow will throw an error and the component won’t be created. |
| output.optional | Map\[String, String Expression\] or Map\[String, Array\[StringExpression\]\] | optional | Dictionary with list of optional attributes of the component. Key \- name of the property, Value \- String Expression with placeholders. If at least one of the placeholders is missing then the synchronisation flow won’t create only this one attribute |
| output.optional.tags | Map\[String, String Expression\] OR MergeOperator | optional | Dictionary with list of optional tags/labels of the component. Key \- name of the tag, Value \- String Expression with placeholders. If at least one of the placeholders is missing then the synchronisation workflow won’t create the only this one attribute. |
| vars | Array\[Argument\] | optional | List attributes. An attribute creates a variable which can be reused in String Expressions. Each attribute has a name, source and set of transformations. |
| conditions | Array\[Condition\] | optional | List of conditions required to create the component. |

Merge strategy: The same output attribute can be created via **output.optional** and **output.required**. Required attributes have precedence over optional. So first we evaluate optional attributes and then override all of them with required attributes. Array attributes are appended instead of overridden (useful for **identifiers**). The same strategy is applied for tags: **output.optional.tags** and **output.required.tags.**

#### OtelRelation \- creates a topology relation form Otel Span

| Field path | Type | Mandatory | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| \_type | String, expected value **OtelRelationMapping** | yes |  |
| output.sourceId | StringExpression with placeholders | yes | Unique identifier of the source component. All placeholders are mandatory. The relation  won’t be created If at least one placeholder is missing  |
| output.targetId | StringExpression with placeholders | yes | Unique identifier of the target component. All placeholders are mandatory. The relation  won’t be created If at least one placeholder is missing  |
| output.type.name | StringExpression with placeholders | yes | Type of the relation to create, even if the expression accepts placeholders the cardinality should be low.  |
| vars | Array\[Variable\] | optional | List variables. Variables can be reused in String Expressions. Each attribute has a name, source and set of transformations. |
| conditions | Array\[Condition\] | optional | List of conditions required to create the relation. |

#### StringExpression

String OR String with placeholders OR placeholder

| String | “value” |
| :---- | :---- |
| String with placeholder | “value\_${input.attributes\[‘service.name’\]}” |
| placeholder | input.attributes\[‘service.name’\] |

A placeholder can refer to an input Span or a Variable. An input span starts with \`*input.*\`, a variable starts with \`*vars.*\`

#### MergeOperator \<\<:

TODO: test it before implementation, this operator is designed to merge one yaml block to another one.  
Merge operator ([https://yaml.org/type/merge.html](https://yaml.org/type/merge.html)) allows to copy all keys from the input to the output. It can be used mostly for **tags**. Examples:

- \<\<: $input.attributes\["telemetry.sdk.\*"\]    \# copies all attributes starting with **telemetry.sdk.** Prefix  
- \<\<: $input.attributes                                \# copies all attributes

#### Variable

Variables can be reused in String Expressions. Each attribute has a name, source and set of transformations.

| Field path | Type | Mandatory | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| name | String | Yes, allowed chars \[a-zA-Z0-9\_\] | An unique identifier of the Variable. |
| source | StringExpression | Yes | Input for the variable, it may be a String value or StringExperssion |
| transformations | List\[Transformation\] | optional | List of transformations to apply on the Source |

Transformations are executed one after another  
vars:  
 \- name: serviceInstanceId  
   source: $input.attributes\['service.instance.id'\]  
   transformations:  
     \- action: orElse  
       args: $input.attributes\['service.name'\]  
     \- action: toLowerCase  
     \- action: append  
       args:  
         prefix: ""  
         suffix: "-suffix"  
Is equivalent to   
input.attributes\['service.instance.id'\].orElse(input.attributes\['service.name'\]).toLowerCase().append(prefix:"", suffix:"-suffix")

#### Transformation

Instructions how to transform one value to another

| Field path | Type | Mandatory | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| action | String | yes | Name of transformation function, e.g. toLowerCase, orElse |
| args | StringExperssion or Map\[String, StringExpression\] | optional | Arguments for the transformation. Some transformations (like toLowerCase) don’t accept any arguments, some transformations accept only one argument (like orElse) so we can provide only one StringExpression. But some of transformations may accept more arguments \- you can provide these arguments as Map\[String, StringExpression\] |

#### Condition

Must-have conditions for component and relationship creation. Conditions are executed one after another 

| Field path | Type | Mandatory | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| if | String | yes | Name of an operation, like **nonEmpty** |
| value | StringExpression | yes | Input value for the **if** operation. |
| args | StringExperssion or Map\[String, StringExpression\], Array\[StringExpression\] | optional | Optional arguments for the **if** operation. Some operations (like nonEmpty) don't accept any arguments, some operations accept only one argument (like equals) so we can provide only one StringExpression. But some of operations (like IN)  may accept more arguments \- you can provide these arguments as Map\[String, StringExpression\] or Array\[StringExpression\] |
| then | **create** OR **reject** OR **continue** (default) | Optional, Default: **continue** | Action taken when the condition is satisfied. By default the component will be created when ALL conditions are met. Allowed actions: **create** **\-** The component is created instantly, regardless of subsequent conditions. If the condition fails then process with the subsequent conditions. **reject** \- Component creation is denied if this condition is met, regardless of subsequent conditions. If the condition fails then process with the subsequent conditions. **continue \-** If this condition is met, proceed to the next. If it's the final condition and met, the component is created. If the condition fails, component creation is denied. |

##### Examples:

###### *\#1*

conditions:  
 \- if: nonEmpty  
   value: $input.attributes\['service.name'\]

Creates if the attribute [**service.name**](http://service.name) **is not empty**

###### *\#2*

conditions:  
 \- if: in  
   value: $input.attributes\['environment'\]  
   args: \["production", "staging"\]

Creates if the attribute **environment** is equal to **production** OR **staging**

##### \#3

**conditions:**  
 **\- if: equals**  
   **value: $input.attributes\['environment'\]**  
   **args: "dev"**  
   **then: reject**  
 **\- if: nonEmpty**  
   **value: $input.attributes\['exception'\] &&**   
   **then: create**  
 **\- if: notEquals**  
   **value: $input.attributes\['namespace'\]**  
   **args: "kube-system"**

Rejects instantly all spans with environment \== “dev”. Otherwise continue with the subsequent conditions, if the span has attribute name “exception” then create the Component  instantly. Otherwise continue with the last condition \- create a component when the attribute “namespace” is different from “kube-system”.

## Sync service implementation

### Kafka & Sharding

#### Producer

| Single Topic for all OTel data | Single Topic for all data from particular StackPack | Topic per Component and Relation |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **\#topics \= 1** | **\#topics \= \#StackPacks** | **\#topics \= \#component \+ \#relations** |
| Message size \= sum of all attributes After optimization(1) we can reduce to only necessary data. **Max: span size** | Message size \= sum of all attributes from particular StackPack After optimization(1) we can reduce to only necessary data. **Max: span size** | Message size \= sum of all attributes from particular Component/Relation After optimization(1) we can reduce to only necessary data. **Max: span size** |
| \#messages \- the lowest possible, no duplication. In the worst case it is equal to \#spans **Max: \#spans** | \#messages \- some attributes are copied between topics so global number of messages may be even \#spans \* \#topics **Max: \#spans \* \#StackPacks** | \#messages \- some attributes are copied between topics so global number of messages may be even \#spans \* \#topics **Max: \#spans \* (\#components \+ \#relations)** |

1) IMO we should implement such optimization ASAP. Of course it becomes more important for Single Topic for all OTel data but still it is worth implementing nevertheless what strategy we are going to use.

![][image3]  
![][image4]  
![][image5]  
So the biggest difference is data replication between topics. **From an OTel collector (producer) perspective it is better to implement one global topic for all Components and Relations**. Moreover we have Components like a ServiceInstance which has all spans attributes. But also we should take into consideration the consumer side and solution where we can partition data. Also one kafka topic can work very well with multi-tenancy and provide data isolation \- a topic per tenant. The last argument is: we can simplify initialization, we have to create a topic once (in the initialization process) not each time when we upload a new StackPack. 

#### Producer Optimization

![][image6]

##### Consumer impact

Consumers are more important than producers, because wrong design can complicate scalability. From a consumer perspective we have to take into consideration if we can achieve horizontal scaling. It may be misleading that with many topics we can shard it easier but it may not be true (there may be only one topic or we may have hot topics with almost all data). Sync Service (consumers) are stateful so we have to send data of the same component to the same instance of Sync Service. So we have to use kafka message keys. The natural choice for that is **externalId**. So the previous optimization causes some problems because if we wrap two Components into one kafka message we can’t generate a stateful message key. Unfortunately, we have to split each OTel span into multiple kafka messages (one per component)  
![][image7]

#### Partitions and a message key

Now we can partition data by component type and external identifier. Example message key **${componentType}|${externalIdentifier}**. It guarantees that all messages for one instance of a Component will be processed by the same consumer (Sync Service). We can also configure the topic to use multiple partitions to parallelize consumption flow. With such a message key we can also avoid hot partitions.  

| Message key | ${componentType}:${externalIdentifier} |
| :---- | :---- |
| \# partitions | \>= \# sync service instances |
| Max \# messages | \# span \* \#ComponentTypes |

#### Consumer

Each Sync Service instance can have one Kafka Consumer to consume all data from a given partition. But each partition can have data of different Component Types but all data related to the same Component will be processed by the same instance of Sync Service. Sync service must then fork the flow to flows for individual Component Types.

# Alternative solutions

We should move entire transformation/computation to one place, so we have two options otel collector and Sync Service. There is a third option to spread computation between these two components to optimize it.

## \#Solution1  \- generic OTel Collector

OTel Collector sends all data (with all attributes) to Sync Service. Sync Service creates a synchronisation stream for each Component Type   
![][image10]  
The solution has an open question: “how to create a Stream Source for Sync service?” In this solution from one input Span (from kafka) we can generate multiple Components and Relation. So we have two options:

- We can create multiple Sources (one per stream), each Source will be another Kafka Consumer Group.   
  - Pros: one slow stream doesn’t affect rest of streams  
  - Cons: We consume the same data from kafka many times (multiple consumer groups) of course it is better to consume it once  
- Consume kafka data once and then “fork” it in the Stream to multiple Sinks  
  - Pros: consume data once  
  - Cons: one slow Sink affects rest of the of streams  
    

Kafka doesn't have a problem with multiple consumer groups, but in our scenario we are going to consume data almost at the same time so we can consume it one. We can mix solutions and implement one consumer group and then implement throttling for slow streams (some messages will be deleted). IMO, we need a mechanism to drop messages if streams are too slow \- otherwise the topic may grow and input Spans won’t be processed real time but with constantly increasing delay.

## \#Solution2 \- generic Sync Service

OTel collector receives configuration (from StackPack) and then prepare for each Span creates zero, one or more Components and a Relation which matches to an Component definition in the StackPack. Then the Sync service receives a set of Components and Relations and stores them in the database.  
![][image11]  
One open questions:

- How to provide StackPack configuration to OpenTelemetry Collector. There are multiple salutations. We can use a pulling mechanism, we can use compacted topics and store the newest configuration there. It is a secondary problem and shouldn’t have impact on what solution we decide to implement.

# Comparison

|  | \#Solution1  \- generic OTel Collector | \#Solution2 \- generic Sync Service |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Amount of data transferred from OTel Collector to Sync Service (via Receiver and Kafka) | Almost all data from each Span are transferred once. Even if the Span contains irrelevant data we transfer everything.  **\#messages** \= \#spans **Message size** \=\~ Span size | Collectors can filter only relevant Spans and then uses only necessary attributes to a Component. **\#messages** \- unknown, it may be less than \#spans but it can be even X times more.  **Message size** \< \= Span size, it depends how many attributes we use to create a Component. |
| Scalability | Not supported ??? | OTel collectors support horizontal scaling, but we need to run another collector to play role of a Load Balancer |
| Possiblities |  | We can create an opensource exporter and ask clients to install it on their cluster. So all computations will be done at edge \- it won’t generate an extra load for our infrastructure. |

The complexity of these two solutions is similar, we have to solve different types of problems. It is very difficult to decide which one is better. For one client Solution \#1 can be better but for another \-  the second can be better. Everything depends on how many Component Types we are going to create. What portion of attributes will be used to create a Component, and what % of Spans will be used to create Components.

## \#Solution3 \- improved \#Solution1 (filter Spans and attributes).

We can add some improvements to \#Solution1. Instead of sending all Spans and all attributes from OTel Collector to Sync Service we can filter attributes which are used in the next step (Sync Service) and also filter Spans which have at least on relevant attribute. 

![][image12]

|  | \#Solution1  \- generic OTel Collector | \#Solution3 \- improved \#Solution1 |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Amount of data transferred from OTel Collector to Sync Service (via Receiver and Kafka) | Almost all data from each Span are transferred once. Even if the Span contains irrelevant data we transfer everything.  **\#messages** \= \#spans **Message size** \=\~ Span size | Only relevant Spans and attributes are transferred. **\#messages** \<= \#spans **Message size** \<= Span size |

Details:

- If at least one param of **externalId** is empty/not defined then the component won’t be created  
- If one element of **data** is missing then only that one element is ignored but the component will be created, if you want to skip the Component then you have to use the **conditions** section.  
- Relation requires **sourceId** and **targetId** , if at least one of them is missing then the Relation won’t be created  
- **Args** uses pipeline transformations, one is executed after another e.g. 

	    
args:  
 \- name: serviceInstanceId  
   source: input.attributes\['service.instance.id'\]  
   transformations:  
     \- action: orElse  
       value: input.attributes\['service.name'\]  
     \- action: toLowerCase  
     \- action: append  
       value: "-suffix"

Is equivalent to   
input.attributes\['service.instance.id'\].orElse(input.attributes\['service.name'\]).append("-sufix")
